{"id":"2111.04690","submitter":"Nikolay Geravker","authors":"Nikolai Geravker, Svetlana Puzynina","title":"Abelian Nivat's conjecture for non-rectangular patterns","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this paper, we study the relation between periodicity of two-dimensional\nwords and their abelian pattern complexity. A pattern $\\cal{P}$ in\n$\\mathbb{Z}^n$ is the set of all translations of some finite subset $F$ of\n$\\mathbb{Z}^n$. An $F$-factor of an infinite word is a finite word restricted\nto $F$. Then the pattern complexity over a pattern $\\mathcal{P}$ counts the\nnumber of distinct $F$-factors of an infinite word, for $P\\in \\mathcal{P}$. Two\nfinite words are called abelian equivalent if for each letter of the alphabet,\nthey contain the same numbers of occurrences of this letter. The abelian\npattern complexity counts the number of $F$-factors up to abelian equivalence.\nAs the main result of the paper, we characterize two-dimensional convex\npatterns with the following property: if abelian pattern complexity over a\npattern $\\cal{P}$ is equal to 1, then the word is fully periodic. Similar\nresult holds for a function on $\\mathbb{Z}^2$ instead of a word and for\nconstant sums instead of abelian complexity equal to 1. In dimensional 1, we\ncharacterize patterns for which there exist non-constant functions with\nconstant sums.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 8 Nov 2021 18:10:04 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 24 Dec 2021 18:34:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-12-28"}
